# Developer Specification — Alphanumeria

This document defines the structural rules for the developer layer of Alphanumeria.

The developer layer introduces system-level encoding using digits 7, 8, and 9.

---

## Structural Symbols

7 → start  
8 → separator (space / AND)  
9 → end  

---

## Parsing Rule

A valid structured string:

- must begin with 7  
- may include 8 as separators  
- must terminate with 9  

---

## Structure Format

General form:

7 [encoded segments separated by 8] 9

---

## Example

Plain:
HELLO WORLD

Level 1:
H2LL4 W4RLD

Structured:
7H2LL48W4RLD9

---

## Breakdown

- 7 → start of sequence  
- H2LL4 → HELLO  
- 8 → separator  
- W4RLD → WORLD  
- 9 → end of sequence  

---

## Identity Encoding (ONID)

Plain:
BERNARD FREEMAN

Level 1:
B2RN1RD FR22M1N

Structured:
7B2RN1RD8FR22M1N9

---

## Validation Rules

A structured string is valid if:

- it begins with 7  
- it ends with 9  
- all separators are 8  
- no invalid digits (outside 1–9) are used  
- inner content follows Level 1 rules  

---

## Invalid Examples

Missing start:
H2LL48W4RLD9 ❌

Missing end:
7H2LL48W4RLD ❌

Incorrect separator:
7H2LL45W4RLD9 ❌

---

## Design Principles

- deterministic  
- minimal  
- human-readable + machine-parseable  
- consistent across all implementations  

---

## Layer Model

Alphanumeria operates in two layers:

- Layer 1 (1–6) → meaning  
- Developer Layer (7–9) → structure  

This enables:
- readable encoding  
- structured communication  
- programmatic interpretation  

---

## Future Extensions

The developer layer may support:

- nested structures  
- version indicators  
- metadata flags  
- multi-level parsing  

---

## Summary

7 starts the structure.  
8 separates meaning.  
9 completes the sequence.  

---

Alphanumeria is not only readable.

It is structured.
